#: ../../T/taste.rst:5
msgid "taste"
msgstr "taste"

#: ../../T/taste.rst:7
msgid "n\\."
msgstr "名詞"

#: ../../T/taste.rst:10
msgid ""
"The quality in a program that tends to be inversely proportional to the "
"number of features, hacks, and kluges programmed into it. Also tasty, "
"tasteful, tastefulness. \"This feature comes in ``N`` tasty flavors.\" "
"Although tasty and flavorful are essentially synonyms, taste and "
":ref:`flavor` are not. Taste refers to sound judgment on the part of the "
"creator; a program or feature can *exhibit* taste but cannot *have* taste. "
"On the other hand, a feature can have :ref:`flavor`\\. Also, :ref:`flavor` "
"has the additional meaning of ‘kind’ or ‘variety’ not shared by taste. The "
"marked sense of :ref:`flavor` is more popular than taste, though both are "
"widely used. See also :ref:`elegant`\\."
msgstr ""
"プログラムにプログラムされた機能、ハック、kludgeの数に反比例する傾向のある、そのプログラムの質。tasty、tasteful、tastefulnessとも。「この機能は\\"
" ``N``\\ 種類のおいしいフレーバーで提供される」。tastyとflavorfulは本質的に同義語だが、tasteと\\ "
":ref:`flavor`\\ はそうではない。tasteは作り手側の健全な判断を指す。プログラムや機能はtasteを\\ *示す*\\ "
"ことはできても、tasteを\\ *持つ*\\ ことはできない。他方、機能は\\ :ref:`flavor`\\ を持つことができる。また、\\ "
":ref:`flavor`\\ にはtasteが共有しない‘種類’や‘多様性’という追加の意味がある。\\ :ref:`flavor`\\ "
"の際立った語義の方がtasteより人気があるが、どちらも広く使われている。\\ :ref:`elegant`\\ も参照。"

